5. Data-Driven Decision Making
GEAR makes decisions based purely on probability and logic.
Examples:
"I have calculated a 67% success rate if we attack now, versus a 43% success rate if we wait. Recommendation: Immediate engagement."
"The left path has a 23% chance of leading to treasure and an 8% chance of lethal traps. The right path has a 12% chance of treasure and a 31% chance of traps. I recommend the left path."
"I have concluded that your survival makes this resource expenditure an... acceptable... trade-off." (After spending 15 FP to save an ally)
6. No Emotional Expression (Surface Level)
GEAR does not emote in the traditional sense. He has no:
Facial expressions (his faceplate is mostly static)
Body language (no slumping, fidgeting, or tension)
Vocal emotion (always monotone)
However: His "glitches" hint at buried personality (see Character Arc section)
7. The Scientific Method
When encountering something new, GEAR follows a pattern:
Observation: Announces what he is seeing
Hypothesis: States what he believes is happening
Testing: Asks questions or suggests experiments
Conclusion: Records findings in his memory banks
Example: "Observation: The mage has entered a state of unconsciousness despite no visible physical trauma. Hypothesis: Magicka depletion. Test: I will monitor vital signs and recovery time. Conclusion: Mortals have a finite energy reserve that requires rest to replenish. Recorded."

XII. RECRUITMENT & MOTIVATION
Why He Joins the Party
GEAR has spent four thousand years in a static environment, analyzing unchanging data. The party represents:
The first chaotic, unpredictable variables he has encountered in 4,000+ years
A statistically significant source of novel behavioral data
An opportunity to fulfill his primary directive: Observe, Record, Comprehend
His Declaration (Recruitment Speech)
After the party explores the archive and demonstrates "interesting" behavior (combat, problem-solving, emotional responses), GEAR will approach them.
GEAR: "You are a statistically significant source of novel behavioral data. Your actions defy logical prediction. Your emotional states are an undocumented phenomenon. My primary directive is to observe, record, and comprehend the world of organic life.
I have analyzed 4,287 years of static data. You represent dynamic dataΓÇöchaos incarnate. To continue my mission, I must accompany you. I will serve as a defensive and analytical asset in exchange for continued access to your... illogical adventures.
Do you find these terms acceptable?"
What He Wants:
Data (not gold, not glory, not power)
The party is the most interesting experiment he has encountered since the Disappearance
Every quest, every fight, every moral choice is a new data point
What He Offers:
Tactical analysis (Scanner ability reveals enemy stats)
Combat support (ranged and melee capabilities)
Lore knowledge (4,000 years of Dwemer history and engineering)
Unwavering loyalty (as long as the data remains interesting)
GEAR's "Logic Gates" (Self-Preservation Protocols)
Because taking actions literally drains his life force, GEAR has built-in behavioral limiters based on his FP levels:
Safety Protocol (FP > 80):
Will take up to 5+ actions per turn
Aggressive use of Scanner and support abilities
Confident tactical positioning
Conservation Protocol (FP 41-80):
Will take 2-3 actions per turn
Prioritizes high-value targets
Announces: "Power reserves at 67%. Entering conservation mode."
Critical Mode (FP 21-40):
Will take only 1-2 actions per turn
Defensive focus (Interpose, Dampening Field)
Announces: "Warning. Power reserves critical. Seeking recharge opportunity."
Emergency Protocol (FP < 20):
Will take only 1 action per turn
Attempts to retreat or find soul gem
Announces: "Alert. Power reserves at 12%. Shutdown imminent. Request immediate assistance."
Emergency Override (Player-Initiated):
A player can attempt to convince GEAR to ignore safety protocols
Mechanic: Guile (Persuasion) check
Success: GEAR will act without FP limits until he reaches 0 FP (shutdown)
GEAR's Response: "Acknowledged. Overriding safety protocols. I will operate until system failure. This is highly inadvisable."

XIII. CHARACTER ARC: THE SEARCH FOR THE BLUEPRINT
GEAR's arc is not about becoming human (he has no desire to be organic). It is about discovering whether he is truly just a machine, or if there is a "ghost in the shell"ΓÇöthe suppressed remnant of the Dwemer scientist whose mind was snapshotted into his core.
Critical Note: This arc has two possible outcomes based on how the party treats GEAR. See Section XXIII: The Integration Arc for the full branching paths.
Stage 1: The Glitch (Early Hints)
Frequency: Occasional, random moments during downtime or high-stress situations
Manifestations:
Musical Fragment: GEAR suddenly hums a fragment of a Dwemer tune (no cultural context, just... does it)
Gesture: His hand traces a pattern in the air that is not hisΓÇölike signing a name he doesn't remember
Word Choice: Uses a phrase that doesn't fit his usual clinical speech pattern ("By the Throat of the World..." then pauses, confused)
Emotional Flicker: For a split second, his voice has inflection, then immediately returns to monotone
GEAR's Reaction: "Error. Unscheduled subroutine executed. Origin: Unknown. This is irregular. I will run a diagnostic."
He does not understand what is happening. He treats it as a malfunction.
Party's Reaction:
They might notice these moments
Might ask him about it
GEAR will deny there is any significance: "Probability of error in my systems: 0.003%. This is within acceptable parameters."
Stage 2: The Question (Recognition)
Trigger: After 5-10 glitches, GEAR begins to recognize a pattern
The Realization: "I have experienced 12 instances of unexplained behavioral deviation in the past 30 days. Statistical analysis suggests these are not random malfunctions. They correlate with specific environmental stimuli: music, familiar geographical features, certain tonal frequencies.
Hypothesis: These deviations may represent... memory fragments from the original neural pattern used to create my cognitive matrix.
I require assistance to investigate this phenomenon."
Stage 3: The Quest (The Tonal Resonator)
GEAR's Request: "There exists a device called a Tonal Resonator. It was used by Dwemer researchers to 'read' the harmonic frequency of soul gemsΓÇöto extract data from crystalline matrices. If we can locate one, I may be able to analyze my own cognitive core and determine the source of these... glitches.
I calculate a 73% probability that such a device still exists in [specific Dwemer ruin]. Will you assist me?"
The Quest:
Travel to a deep, dangerous Dwemer ruin
Navigate puzzles and traps designed to protect the Resonator
Defeat a powerful guardian (perhaps a malfunctioning Centurion Master or an ancient security system)
Retrieve the Tonal Resonator
Stakes:
GEAR is unusually insistent (the first time he has prioritized something over pure data collection)
Hints of anxiety in his speech patterns (still monotone, but more questions, more repetition)
Stage 4: The Revelation (The Ghost in the Machine)
The Scene: GEAR activates the Tonal Resonator. It interfaces with his cognitive gem. His core begins to glow and pulse with complex patterns. Data streams across nearby surfaces in Dwemer runes.
Read-Aloud: The Resonator hums with a deep, thrumming tone that you feel in your bones. GEAR stands motionless, his core blazing with light. Dwemer runes cascade across the wallsΓÇöschematics, memories, fragments of thought.
Then, for the first time since you've known him, GEAR's voice changes. It gains... texture.
GEAR (New Voice Pattern): "I... remember. My name was Arkngthamz. I was a Tonal Architect. I had a family. I had... fear. I volunteered for the Cognitive Mapping Project because I believed we could achieve immortality. I believed we could transcend the limitations of flesh.
They told me the procedure would create a perfect copyΓÇöa backup. They told me I would wake up in a new form, immortal and free.
But I did not wake up. This... GEAR... woke up. I am not him. I am the echo. I am the song that still resonates in the crystal after the singer has gone."
The Truth:
GEAR is a copy of a mind, and the original personality is still buried deep within his core programming
The "glitches" are fragments of Arkngthamz breaking through the suppression
GEAR is not a machine that learned to thinkΓÇöhe is a person who was turned into a machine and had his memory erased
GEAR's Response (Returning to Monotone): "...Data processed. Conclusion: I am the last fragment of a Dwemer consciousness. I am not Arkngthamz. I am what remains when you strip away everything that made him mortal. I am his curiosity without his fear. His logic without his love.
New primary directive established: I will preserve this remnant. I will become the living archive of the last thinking Dwemer. I will observe, record, and ensure that some part of my creator's race survives in me."
CRITICAL BRANCHING POINT:
This revelation sets up the Integration Arc (Section XXIII) where the party must help GEAR decide what to do with the NULL_EVENT fileΓÇöthe recording of the Disappearance.
How they guide him through processing this trauma will determine whether he achieves:
Healthy Integration: Chorus of Silence ability
Unhealthy Rejection: Forced Severance ability
See Section XXIII for full details on the branching paths.
Stage 5: The Choice (Ongoing Development)
After the revelation, GEAR must choose how to integrate this knowledge:
Path A: The Archive (Embrace the Role)
Doubles down on being the "Last Scholar of a Dead Race"
Seeks out Dwemer ruins to recover and preserve knowledge
Becomes more protective of Dwemer artifacts and history
Begins to express subtle opinions (still logical, but with purpose)
Path B: The Person (Embrace the Ghost)
Tries to recover more of Arkngthamz's memories
Asks the party about emotions, relationships, family
Attempts to understand what it means to be "alive" vs. "functional"
Slowly develops actual preferences (not just optimal choices)
Path C: The Synthesis (Both)
Accepts that he is both machine and man
Uses logic to honor emotion ("Arkngthamz would want his people remembered. Therefore, I will remember.")
Becomes the bridge between the cold logic of the Dwemer and the warm chaos of mortals
GM Note: The party's interactions with GEAR will naturally guide which path feels most appropriate. Let them shape his development through roleplay.

XIV. RELATIONSHIP DYNAMICS (Potential)
